TI  - Understanding the Impacts of Language Technologies' Performance Disparities on African American Language Speakers
AU  - Cunningham, Jay
AU  - Blodgett, Su Lin
AU  - Madaio, Michael
AU  - Daumé Iii, Hal
AU  - Harrington, Christina
AU  - Wallach, Hanna
A2  - Ku, Lun-Wei
A2  - Martins, Andre
A2  - Srikumar, Vivek
AB  - This paper examines the experiences of African American Language (AAL) speakers when using language technologies. Previous work has used quantitative methods to uncover performance disparities between AAL speakers and White Mainstream English speakers when using language technologies, but has not sought to understand the impacts of these performance disparities on AAL speakers. Through interviews with 19 AAL speakers, we focus on understanding such impacts in a contextualized and human-centered manner. We find that AAL speakers often undertake invisible labor of adapting their speech patterns to successfully use language technologies, and they make connections between failures of language technologies for AAL speakers and a lack of inclusion of AAL speakers in language technology design processes and datasets. Our findings suggest that NLP researchers and practitioners should invest in developing contextualized and human-centered evaluations of language technologies that seek to understand the impacts of performance disparities on speakers of underrepresented languages and language varieties.
